I have some stuff
I need to finish early

18:12.395 --> 18:15.659
so I can get to
Patricia's career day.

18:15.703 --> 18:17.183
You ever done
one of those before?

18:17.226 --> 18:19.968
- No.
- Wait, you got a plan?

18:20.011 --> 18:22.144
Those kids
can be rough, man.

18:22.188 --> 18:24.755
It's not like
standing up

18:24.799 --> 18:26.670
and talking in front of
a group of 40-year-olds,

18:26.714 --> 18:28.542
I can tell you that much.

18:28.585 --> 18:30.805
Career day is an event.

18:30.848 --> 18:34.156
It's a happening. It's a happening
of monumental proportions.

18:34.200 --> 18:36.506
Those little fuckers
can be brutal.

18:36.550 --> 18:38.160
You-You've been to one?

18:38.204 --> 18:40.510
Last year. My nephew.

18:40.554 --> 18:42.425
I was sure that
they were gonna love me,

18:42.469 --> 18:45.515
that I was gonna leave
that classroom a champ.

18:45.559 --> 18:48.692
They made me
feel like a loser.

18:48.736 --> 18:50.694
Let me give you
some advice.

18:50.738 --> 18:53.784
Don't lie. They can tell,
and they hate you for it.

18:53.828 --> 18:56.744
- I don't care what they think.
- Yeah, but Patricia cares.

18:56.787 --> 18:58.746
Oh.

18:58.789 --> 19:02.576
We've got a department meeting
in the conference room.

19:02.619 --> 19:05.492
Building security
called it.

19:05.535 --> 19:07.624
Come on.
I'll race you.

19:10.627 --> 19:13.891
All right, everyone,
stop your talking.

19:13.935 --> 19:16.067
Stop your talking!

19:21.638 --> 19:23.684
My name's
Arthur Schneedy.

19:23.727 --> 19:27.253
Corporate transferred me over
here to shape this department up,

19:27.296 --> 19:29.429
and shape it up I shall.

19:31.344 --> 19:33.737
I want to be brief so we can all get
back to work, so I'm just gonna

19:33.781 --> 19:37.088
turn it over to the head of building
security, Melanie Brickman.

19:37.132 --> 19:39.482
- Melanie, you want to take it?
- Uh, it's Melissa, sir.

19:39.526 --> 19:42.137
- Melissa. Melissa Brickman.
- Thank you.

19:42.181 --> 19:44.226
Good morning, people.

19:44.270 --> 19:46.750
My name's
Melissa Brickman.

19:46.794 --> 19:49.144
My friends call me Brick,

19:49.188 --> 19:51.190
but none of you
are my friends,

19:51.233 --> 19:53.888
so you can just disregard that
little peek behind the curtain.

19:53.931 --> 19:56.717
I'm sure you've all noticed

19:56.760 --> 19:59.633
the yellow caution tape
blocking off the hallway,

19:59.676 --> 20:02.026
And I'm sure
the "foodies" among you

20:02.070 --> 20:06.161
have noticed the department
kitchen is closed.

20:06.205 --> 20:07.597
Right?

20:07.641 --> 20:09.643
Well, I'm here
to explain why.

20:09.686 --> 20:12.167
Got here around 5:00
this morning.

20:12.211 --> 20:14.952
Did my usual rounds.
Nothing was out of the ordinary.

20:14.996 --> 20:17.216
Everything seemed
hunky-dory.

20:19.130 --> 20:22.264
It wasn't until about 6:00,
when Mr. Schneedy called

20:22.308 --> 20:24.310
and informed me

20:24.353 --> 20:27.704
that something was,
in fact, amiss.

20:28.879 --> 20:31.142
Mr. Schneedy,

20:31.186 --> 20:33.014
you wanna go ahead and tell them
what you told me?

20:33.057 --> 20:35.277
First thing I did
in the morning,

20:35.321 --> 20:37.453
I made a beeline
for the coffee machine.

20:37.497 --> 20:40.326
I fired that baby up,
I gave her a few minutes,

20:40.369 --> 20:44.286
came back to pour myself
a cup of joe.

20:44.330 --> 20:47.289
but when I tipped the carafe,
nothing came out.

20:47.333 --> 20:49.726
Not a goddamn drop.

20:52.860 --> 20:56.037
At first I was confused,
I was disoriented.

20:56.080 --> 20:58.126
And then I spotted it.

20:58.169 --> 21:02.086
The power cord
had been slashed.

21:02.913 --> 21:04.393
That's right.

21:04.437 --> 21:07.744
Somebody sabotaged
the coffee machine.

21:11.008 --> 21:13.272
Ah, but it gets worse.

21:15.143 --> 21:18.320
Next to the broken
appliance,

21:18.364 --> 21:20.279
I found
the following note:

21:20.322 --> 21:23.456
"Fuck Field Publishing."

21:23.499 --> 21:27.286
And it is adorned
with a god-awful drawing

21:27.329 --> 21:29.331
of a human penis,

21:29.375 --> 21:32.595
just shy of climax.

21:32.639 --> 21:34.684
Now, once Mr. Schneedy

21:34.728 --> 21:36.469
informed us
about the crime,

21:36.512 --> 21:39.341
my boys did a sweep
of the department kitchen

21:39.385 --> 21:41.561
and concluded that

21:41.604 --> 21:43.476
the machine
had been sabotaged,

21:43.519 --> 21:46.479
most likely
over the weekend.

21:46.522 --> 21:49.873
So, the only people who
would've had access are

21:49.917 --> 21:53.050
employees of
Field Publishing,

21:53.094 --> 21:55.009
accounts department,

21:55.052 --> 21:57.011
which means
everyone in this room.

21:57.054 --> 21:59.622
Now, Mr. Schneedy has
requested an investigation,

21:59.666 --> 22:02.669
so we're gonna be setting up shop
in the conference room next door.

22:02.712 --> 22:06.499
We're just gonna ask you all to
stop by, answer a few questions.

22:06.542 --> 22:10.111
With all of your cooperation,
we hope to settle this matter

22:10.154 --> 22:11.939
by the end of the day.

22:14.071 --> 22:16.596
That's all I have for them
at this point, sir.

22:21.731 --> 22:24.430
I'm not a stupid man.

22:26.693 --> 22:28.390
I get it. I'm hip.

22:28.434 --> 22:30.305
Let's keep it real.

22:31.611 --> 22:33.656
I know what
you're all thinking.

22:33.700 --> 22:35.441
New guy comes in.

22:35.484 --> 22:37.225
Whoa.

22:37.268 --> 22:41.142
he's overreacting to
a relatively minor incident,

22:41.185 --> 22:43.536
but let me be clear:

22:43.579 --> 22:47.409
This is not about
an electrical appliance.

22:47.453 --> 22:50.194
This is about vandalism.

22:52.588 --> 22:55.330
All right, you can go.

22:55.374 --> 22:58.464
One more thing. Uh, when
you're done talking to Brick,

22:58.507 --> 23:02.206
I want you to shoot by my
office, introduce yourselves.

23:02.250 --> 23:03.947
I want you to come prepared
with your name,

23:03.991 --> 23:06.515
your favorite work
achievement,

23:06.559 --> 23:08.430
and one interesting fact
about yourself.

23:08.474 --> 23:11.825
It'll be a good way for me
to get to know you all.

23:15.089 --> 23:17.004
- This guy's dead.
- Yeah.

23:17.047 --> 23:18.701
Well, this is
how I found him.

23:18.745 --> 23:20.442
He was lying dead
like this outside

23:20.486 --> 23:22.488
- by a pile of manure.
- A big pile of manure.

23:22.531 --> 23:24.881
He was outside?

23:24.925 --> 23:27.406
- Yes.
- And how did he get inside?

23:28.494 --> 23:30.757
- We moved him.
- You moved him?

23:30.800 --> 23:33.107
You bet we did.

23:33.150 --> 23:35.631
I mean, we had to wheelbarrow him
up those stairs. It was a workout.

23:35.675 --> 23:37.894
Do you know that moving
a dead person

23:37.938 --> 23:39.461
without the consent
of the family

23:39.505 --> 23:41.985
or civic authority
is illegal?

23:42.029 --> 23:43.813
- Totally!
- Wha-- Wha--

23:43.857 --> 23:45.511
She gave the orders
on that one.

23:45.554 --> 23:47.687
Well, what were we
supposed to do?

23:47.730 --> 23:50.167
We can't leave a corpse
in the middle of a field.

23:50.211 --> 23:52.169
This school
isn't public.

23:52.213 --> 23:53.867
Next time you move
a dead body,

23:53.910 --> 23:55.608
just make sure you ask
permission first.

23:55.651 --> 23:57.827
Well, hopefully
there won't be a next time.

23:57.871 --> 24:00.395
Lady, there's always
a next time.

24:00.439 --> 24:02.615
Well, aren't you going to
take him with you?

24:02.658 --> 24:05.444
- We're paramedics.
- So?

24:05.487 --> 24:08.447
We don't deal with dead bodies,
we deal with dying people.

24:08.490 --> 24:10.579
Whoa! So you're just
gonna leave him here?

24:10.623 --> 24:15.018
We can't just drive dead bodies
around the city, okay?

24:15.062 --> 24:18.195
We need to keep our van open
for real medical emergencies.

24:18.239 --> 24:21.068
You know, people with strokes
or heart attacks.

24:21.111 --> 24:23.723
People that have fallen off of
buildings, that sort of thing.

24:23.766 --> 24:25.812
Well, what are we supposed
to do with him?

24:27.291 --> 24:30.469
- Call the coroner.
- Oh, my God. I can't-- No!

24:30.512 --> 24:33.167
You're actually going to leave a
dead body in our teacher's lounge?

24:33.210 --> 24:35.430
You're the one
who moved him.

24:38.564 --> 24:40.479
What are they doing?

24:40.522 --> 24:42.568
They took the donuts.

24:43.830 --> 24:45.962
What... They're not
taking the body?

24:46.006 --> 24:49.226
Well, apparently,
he's too dead for them.

24:49.270 --> 24:51.925
- What?
- Did you tell everyone the lounge is closed?

24:51.968 --> 24:54.884
- Yeah. They weren't too happy.
- No shit.

24:54.928 --> 24:57.496
What about his emergency
contacts?

24:57.539 --> 24:59.410
We don't have anything
on file for him,

24:59.454 --> 25:01.151
so I called
the landscaping company,

25:01.195 --> 25:03.589
but they have four Kevins
on staff.

25:03.632 --> 25:06.417
What? Ha!

25:06.461 --> 25:09.856
Are you serious? They got four
gardeners over there named Kevin?

25:09.899 --> 25:11.510
Yeah. So?

25:11.553 --> 25:13.903
So, I'm still trying to
absorb the fact

25:13.947 --> 25:15.688
that there's one gardener
named Kevin,

25:15.731 --> 25:18.647
and you come in here
and tell me there are four?

25:18.691 --> 25:21.345
I feel like it's a set
of Russian dolls.

25:21.389 --> 25:23.913
I just keep, Kevin, Kevin, Kevin,
Kevin, Kevin, Kevin, Kevin!

25:23.957 --> 25:26.089
- Kevins coming out of my ears!
- Stop!

25:26.133 --> 25:30.137
Just find out which Kevin he is
and contact his family.

25:30.180 --> 25:34.620
In the meantime, I am going to
reach out to the coroner.

25:34.663 --> 25:36.752
Mindy, Mindy, Mindy, wait.
Mindy, Mindy--

25:36.796 --> 25:39.363
The Bayeux Tapestry
is a record

25:39.407 --> 25:42.105
of all the Norman conquests,
which is amazing,

25:42.149 --> 25:44.630
because they were actually
able to weave and--

25:46.153 --> 25:48.764
All right, guys,
see you after art class.

26:12.919 --> 26:14.703
Excuse me.

26:14.747 --> 26:16.531
Can I have a word?

26:16.575 --> 26:18.011
Um, sure.

26:19.403 --> 26:22.363
In private,
if you don't mind.

26:22.406 --> 26:24.234
Okay.

26:29.239 --> 26:31.198
Oh, my gosh!

26:31.241 --> 26:33.461
- Would you like a Rolo?
- What are Rolos?

26:33.504 --> 26:36.769
They're candies.
Adult candies.

26:37.813 --> 26:39.902
Thank you.

26:42.688 --> 26:45.604
So, um, what did you
want to talk to me about?

26:45.647 --> 26:48.302
- I wanted to thank you for helping me this morning.
- Oh, yeah.

26:48.345 --> 26:50.434
Don't worry about it.

26:54.395 --> 26:56.223
It's tough being
the new kid.

26:56.266 --> 26:58.921
People, they seem
to pick on you.

26:58.965 --> 27:00.923
- Yeah.
- I'm used to it, though.

27:00.967 --> 27:03.012
I've been to tons
of different schools.

27:03.056 --> 27:05.885
- You have?
- I just moved from London.

27:05.928 --> 27:09.453
I've lived everywhere--
Chicago, New York,

27:09.497 --> 27:11.325
Mumbai--
that was hot.

27:13.153 --> 27:15.372
- I'm Darius.
- Nice to meet you.

27:15.416 --> 27:17.636
I was named after
Darius the Great.

27:18.985 --> 27:20.769
Who is Darius the Great?

27:20.813 --> 27:23.380
- A musician.
- Cool.

27:23.424 --> 27:26.645
Well, I'm Patricia.
I was named after my grandma.

27:26.688 --> 27:29.865
- I bet she was a lovely woman.
- She's not dead.

27:29.909 --> 27:32.302
Oh, good.

27:36.524 --> 27:38.744
Hey, Christian.

27:41.181 --> 27:43.226
You'll like this.

27:43.270 --> 27:46.926
Mike Friedlander shat his pants
in my class this morning.

27:46.969 --> 27:49.711
Right there
at his desk.

27:49.755 --> 27:51.757
He gets this concentrated
look on his face,

27:51.800 --> 27:54.281
and I'm thinking,
there's no way

27:54.324 --> 27:58.067
he's that into my lecture
on sanding and then... pfft!

27:58.111 --> 28:02.376
Whole room smells like a five-week-old
order of chicken tikka masala.

28:03.638 --> 28:05.466
The boy
is 12 years old.

28:05.509 --> 28:08.382
When does it end?

28:08.425 --> 28:10.689
You all right?
What's going on?

28:13.692 --> 28:16.607
When a man loses
everything,

28:16.651 --> 28:18.914
what's he got left?

28:18.958 --> 28:22.048
Is this a trick question
or something?

28:22.875 --> 28:24.093
No.

28:25.878 --> 28:28.054
Uh... nothing.

28:28.097 --> 28:31.361
If a man loses everything,
he has nothing left.

28:32.319 --> 28:33.842
Yeah, that's about right.

28:33.886 --> 28:38.020
You all right?
You seem more down than usual.

28:39.805 --> 28:41.894
Over the weekend, I had this realization.
It's like,

28:41.937 --> 28:46.246
- we spend our entire lives--
- Shit, they got the table saw.

28:46.289 --> 28:48.770
Isaac!
Put the blade down!

28:48.814 --> 28:50.990
Isaac!

28:51.033 --> 28:53.383
- How long have you lived here?
- My whole life.

28:53.427 --> 28:55.168
Your whole life?

28:55.211 --> 28:57.866
Wow. Must be nice to have
that kind of stability.

28:57.910 --> 29:00.564
- I guess.
- I used to.

29:00.608 --> 29:02.305
Then my mom died.

29:02.349 --> 29:03.959
Your mom died?

29:04.003 --> 29:06.048
Yeah.

29:06.092 --> 29:07.789
My mom did too.

29:07.833 --> 29:09.530
Really? That's so--

29:09.573 --> 29:13.012
Uh, I think we got to go
to class now.

29:13.055 --> 29:14.622
- Right.
- Bye.

29:14.665 --> 29:17.103
Patricia!

29:18.104 --> 29:19.409
Yes?

29:21.847 --> 29:25.024
- Will you go with me?
- Darius--

29:25.067 --> 29:28.375
Look, I know it's
a big decision, so...

29:28.418 --> 29:31.595
how about you think about it and
tell me at lunch before Career Day?

29:33.032 --> 29:34.250
Sure.

29:34.294 --> 29:35.556
Okay.

29:35.599 --> 29:37.471
Patricia?

29:45.392 --> 29:48.090
We got to find
the Swiss Army knife.

29:48.134 --> 29:50.789
- What?
- Find the Swiss Army knife.

29:50.832 --> 29:52.834
What do you mean,
"find the Swiss Army knife"?

29:52.878 --> 29:54.923
Well, clearly whoever did this
used a Swiss Army knife.

29:54.967 --> 29:58.448
- Why do you say that?
- I watch a lot of NCIS, Daniel,

29:58.492 --> 30:02.496
and after a while you pick up on
certain investigative tactics.

30:02.539 --> 30:04.150
Isn't NCISthe navy one?

30:04.193 --> 30:06.065
Just because
the crimes are aquatic

30:06.108 --> 30:07.806
don't mean that the techniques
are any less useful.

30:07.849 --> 30:10.243
Gotta pay attention
to the little details.

30:10.286 --> 30:12.680
That cord was cut clean.

30:12.723 --> 30:14.813
That was a sharp blade.

30:14.856 --> 30:17.380
All we got in the kitchen
are those little plastic knives.

30:17.424 --> 30:19.905
You can't even cut a bagel
with one of those.

30:19.948 --> 30:21.994
No.
It's not a scissor.

30:22.037 --> 30:24.039
That'd be like
gnawing at that cord.

30:24.083 --> 30:26.172
Nah,
this is a sharp blade.

30:26.215 --> 30:28.739
Not a little Swiss Army knife
for your cuticles but, like,

30:28.783 --> 30:31.220
a pocket knife,
Swiss Army knife.

30:31.264 --> 30:33.875
- Kinda makes sense.
- "Kinda"?

30:33.919 --> 30:36.617
No, it does make sense.
It's like The Fugitive.

30:36.660 --> 30:39.838
- I don't want to hear about The Fugitiveagain.
- Find the one-armed man.

30:39.881 --> 30:43.189
But we're not looking for a
one-armed man, we're looking for

30:43.232 --> 30:46.192
a two-armed man with a Swiss Army knife.

30:46.235 --> 30:49.412
- This is Daniel. - Daniel,
security is ready to see you.

30:54.983 --> 30:57.246
- How are you, Daniel?
- Good.

30:57.290 --> 31:00.423
Good. Care for anything to drink?
Water, soda, anything like that?

31:00.467 --> 31:02.295
No, thanks.
I'm okay.

31:02.338 --> 31:04.253
Coffee?

31:04.297 --> 31:06.342
I thought the coffee
machine was broken.

31:06.386 --> 31:07.953
I was just kidding.

31:07.996 --> 31:10.129
You got your wits
about you.

31:10.172 --> 31:13.132
You'd be shocked how many
we fool with that one.

31:13.175 --> 31:14.873
Okay, children,

31:14.916 --> 31:17.223
little ones, friends.

31:17.266 --> 31:20.008
Jesus.

31:22.881 --> 31:25.274
Look, um, I know
I said we would be

31:25.318 --> 31:28.712
working on recorders today,
which is fun,

31:28.756 --> 31:31.019
always is, but, um...

31:31.063 --> 31:33.282
there's been
a change of plans.

31:33.326 --> 31:35.981
Uh...
What's up, Nathan?

31:36.024 --> 31:37.852
I need to go
to the bathroom.

31:37.896 --> 31:41.334
I sympathize with you,
my man, but, um,

31:41.377 --> 31:43.510
I can't let anybody
leave today, all right?

31:43.553 --> 31:45.947
The lesson's just
too important,

31:45.991 --> 31:47.557
yeah, and, uh...

31:47.601 --> 31:50.473
it actually might be
the most important lesson

31:50.517 --> 31:53.433
that you've ever learned,
and, uh, trust me,

31:53.476 --> 31:55.914
you'll learn it.

31:55.957 --> 31:59.265
I'll get started.
Okay, so, uh...

31:59.308 --> 32:02.442
today, guys,
I just want to

32:02.485 --> 32:04.705
talk to you about...

32:07.664 --> 32:10.624
- Fear?
- Failure!

32:10.667 --> 32:12.669
Yeah.

32:12.713 --> 32:14.541
Failure.

32:14.584 --> 32:17.413
What time did you arrive
at work this morning, Daniel?

32:17.457 --> 32:19.763
Around 9:00, I think.

32:19.807 --> 32:22.288
When you got here at 9:00,
what did you do?

32:22.331 --> 32:24.551
I walked in,
and I saw,

32:24.594 --> 32:27.641
you know, the...
the crime scene.

32:27.684 --> 32:30.600
I asked what was going on,
and then I went into my office.

32:30.644 --> 32:33.212
Daniel,

32:33.255 --> 32:35.301
look me in the eye.

32:35.344 --> 32:37.912
Did you sabotage
the coffee machine?

32:37.956 --> 32:40.306
- Are you serious?
- Oh, I'm dead serious.

32:40.349 --> 32:42.699
- It's a simple yes-or-no question.
- No.

32:42.743 --> 32:45.659
Daniel,
look me in the eyes.

32:45.702 --> 32:47.530
- Did you sabotage--
- No!

32:47.574 --> 32:49.141
Let me finish
the question.

32:49.184 --> 32:51.012
I know what
you're going to ask.

32:51.056 --> 32:54.059
Wow. You seem to have a strange
affinity for telepathy.

32:54.102 --> 32:57.279
I did not sabotage
the coffee machine.

32:59.194 --> 33:01.327
That'll be all, Mr. Crawford.
Thank you.

33:03.416 --> 33:06.027
- You all right?
- No, it's a full-on interrogation.

33:06.071 --> 33:08.116
What?

33:13.078 --> 33:15.602
Hey, don't forget to
go meet the new boss.

33:17.952 --> 33:19.562
Damn it!

33:20.694 --> 33:22.565
Yell at me...

33:22.609 --> 33:25.046
And it all
boils down to this.

33:25.090 --> 33:27.048
All right, this is the moment
of clarity, wherein

33:27.092 --> 33:30.878
pessimism gives way
to nihilism,

33:30.921 --> 33:34.316
and nihilism gives way
to acceptance, right?

33:34.360 --> 33:37.711
We will all reach this day.

33:38.973 --> 33:40.844
And for me,

33:40.888 --> 33:42.629
that day...

33:43.673 --> 33:45.675
is today.

33:47.329 --> 33:49.462
Today's that day.

33:49.505 --> 33:52.291
- Daniel Crawford.
- Go on in, hon.

33:54.989 --> 33:57.078
